<section xml:id="Section-Geometric-Transformations-of-the-Plane" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Extra Topic: Geometric Transformations of the Plane</title>



<p> 
In <xref ref="exp-shapeTransformation"/>, we saw how geometric shapes in the plane can be manipulated with matrix transformations.  
In this section we will study matrix transformations of the plane in more detail by applying transformations to pixels in photos.  
</p> 

<p> 
We treat every pixel of a picture as a point or a vector in <m>\R^2</m>.  
A transformation is applied to each pixel, and the output pixel is colored the same color as the input pixel. 

The figure below shows the result of one such transformation.
</p> 



<image width="70%">
    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
     <latex-image>
       \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
 \node[inner sep=0pt, anchor=base] (gulls) at (6.25mm,0)
   {\includegraphics[width=25mm]{/workspaces/unl_math314/assets/twobuildings.jpg}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
     </latex-image>
 </image>


<p> 
Not all transformations are matrix transformations.  <xref ref="prob-translation-does-not-work"/> offers a cautionary tale on trying to find a matrix for a transformation when such a matrix does not exist.
Luckily, many familiar transformations, including rotations, scalings, reflections and shears, are matrix transformations. We will focus our attention on those.
</p> 

<p> 
Recall that by <xref ref="obs-imagesofijk"/>, we can find a matrix for each transformation by examining its action on standard basis vectors <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m>. 
</p> 










<subsection xml:id="Subsection-Horizontal-and-Vertical-Scaling">
    <title>Horizontal and Vertical Scaling</title>


<exploration xml:id="init-vertstretch">
    <p>
        Let us attempt to find a matrix <m>M</m> for the transformation <m>T</m> that stretches an image vertically by a factor of 2, as shown in the figure below.  
    </p> 

<sidebyside>
		<image width="55%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
\node[inner sep=0pt, anchor=base] (gulls) at (6.25mm,0)
  {\includegraphics[width=25mm]{/workspaces/unl_math314/assets/images/gulls.jpg}};
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-0.5,0)--(2,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-0.5)--(0,2);
           \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
  
   <image width="55%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2]
 \node[inner sep=0pt, anchor=base]  (stretchedgulls) at (6.25mm,0)
  {\includegraphics[width=25mm]{/workspaces/unl_math314/assets/stretchedgulls.jpg}};
\draw[\lt -\gt ] (-0.5,0)--(2,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-0.5)--(0,2);
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
</sidebyside>

<p> 
Consider what this transformation does to the standard unit vectors.  We observe that <m>T(\mathbf{i})=\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>T(\mathbf{j})=2\mathbf{j}</m>. 
</p> 

<sidebyside>

<image width="55%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]

  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-0.5,0)--(2.5,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-0.5)--(0,2.5);
   \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,0);
   \node[red] at (0.5, -0.2)   (a) {\(\mathbf{i}\)};
    \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(0,1);
    \node[blue] at (-0.2, 0.5)   (b) {\(\mathbf{j}\)};
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
  \quad\quad
    <image width="100%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
\draw[\lt -\gt ] (-0.5,0)--(2.5,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-0.5)--(0,2.5);
  \node[red] at (0.5, -0.2)   (a) {\(T(\mathbf{i})\)};
  \node[blue] at (-0.3, 1)   (b) {\(T(\mathbf{j})\)};
   \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,0);
    \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(0,2);
    
     \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>   
</sidebyside>

<p> 
 This allows us to construct a candidate for the transformation matrix <m>M</m>, by making the images of <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m> the columns of <m>M</m>.  Thus, 

<me>
    M=\begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  0\\
0 \amp  2
\end{bmatrix}
</me>


We can now check to see what this matrix does to an arbitrary point <m>(a, b)</m>.  Treating this point as a vector <m>[a,b]</m>, we compute

<me>
    M=\begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  0\\
0 \amp  2
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}a\\2b\end{bmatrix}
</me>

 Thus, this transformation takes point <m>(a, b)</m> to point <m>(a, 2b)</m>.  So, the proposed transformation doubles all <m>y</m>-coordinates resulting in a vertical stretch by a factor of 2.
    </p>
</exploration>





<p> 
 In general, a vertical stretch (or compression) leaves <m>\mathbf{i}</m> unchanged, and scales the vector <m>\mathbf{j}</m> while preserving its vertical direction.
 Thus, a vertical stretch (or compression) maps <m>\mathbf{i}</m> to <m>\mathbf{i}</m>, and maps <m>\mathbf{j}</m> to <m>k\mathbf{j}</m> for some positive number <m>k</m>. 
 Similarly, a horizontal stretch (or compression) maps <m>\mathbf{i}</m> to <m>k\mathbf{i}</m>, and maps <m>\mathbf{j}</m> to <m>\mathbf{j}</m>.
</p> 

<identity xml:id="form-horvertscaling">
    <title>Horizontal and Vertical Scaling</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A matrix transformation induced by 
  <men xml:id="vscale">
M_v=\begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  0\\
0 \amp  k
\end{bmatrix},
</men>
where (<m>k\gt 0</m>), scales objects in the plane vertically by a factor of <m>k</m>.

A matrix transformation induced by
  <men xml:id="hscale"> 
M_h=\begin{bmatrix}
k \amp  0\\
0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix},
</men>
where (<m>k\gt 0</m>), scales objects in the plane horizontally by a factor of <m>k</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</identity>

<p> 
In stating the above formula we stipulated that <m>k\gt 0</m>.
If we were to allow <m>k</m> to be zero, what would the resulting transformations accomplish? 
In what way would the resulting matrices be fundamentally different from matrices <m>M_v</m> and <m>M_h</m>?
 What would happen if <m>k</m> were allowed to be negative? See <xref ref="prob-k0"/>.
</p> 
</subsection> 



















<subsection xml:id="Subsection-Horizontal-and-Vertical-Shears">
    <title>Horizontal and Vertical Shears</title>

<p> 
A <term>horizontal shear</term> is a transformation that takes an arbitrary point <m>(a, b)</m> and maps it to the point <m>(a+kb, b)</m>. 
The effect of this transformation is that all points along a fixed horizontal line slide to the left or to the right by a fixed amount.
 Note that the higher the point <m>(a, b)</m> is above the <m>x</m>-axis, the greater is the magnitude of <m>kb</m>, resulting in a greater amount of horizontal slide.
</p> 

