<p> 
Adding a scalar multiple of the <m>y</m> component to the <m>x</m> component can be accomplished by matrix multiplication.  Observe that 

<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  k\\
0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}a+kb\\b\end{bmatrix}.
</me>


A <term>vertical shear</term> is a transformation that takes an arbitrary point <m>(a, b)</m> and maps it to the point <m>(a, b+ka)</m>. 
This too, can be accomplished by matrix multiplication.

<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  0\\
k \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}a\\b+ka\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
</p> 

<identity xml:id="form-shears">
    <title>Horizontal and Vertical Shears</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A matrix transformation induced by 
  <men> 
M_{hs}=\begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  k\\
0 \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}
</men>
shears the plane horizontally.

A matrix transformation induced by
  <men> 
M_{vs}=\begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp  0\\
k \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}
</men>
shears the plane vertically.
        </p>
    </statement>
</identity>

