<subsection xml:id="Subsection-Reflections-about-Lines-of-the-Form">
    <title>Reflections about Lines of the Form <m>y=mx</m></title>

    <p> 
When a point is reflected about a line, its image is located on the opposite side of the line and the same distance away from the line as the original point.  
This is another example of a matrix transformation.  
    </p> 

    <p> 
For example, the figure below shows the reflection of point <m>A</m> about line <m>l</m>.  Note that the reflection lies on a line through <m>A</m> perpendicular to <m>l</m>.
    </p> 



<image width="55%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]

   \draw[line width=1pt](-1,2)node[below, left]{\(l\)}--(1,-2);
  \draw[thin, dashed](-2,-1.5)--(2,0.5);
  
  \fill[red](1,0) circle (0.08)node[above]{\(A\)};
  \fill[](-0.6,-0.8) circle (0.08);
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>

<p>  
Our task is to find the matrix of a reflection of the plane about an arbitrary line through the origin.  
</p> 

<exploration xml:id="init-reflectionxyaxes">
    <p>
        In this problem we will find the matrix for the reflection about the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axes.  You can easily do this on your own by finding the images of vectors <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and <m>\mathbf{j}</m>.  
  
  We will start with the reflection about the <m>x</m>-axis.
  
  
<me>
    \mathbf{i}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}\quad\text{maps to}\quad\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix},
</me>

  
  
<me>
    \mathbf{j}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}\quad\text{maps to}\quad\begin{bmatrix}0\\-1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

  
  So, the matrix that induces the reflection about the <m>x</m>-axis is
  
<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}1\amp 0\\0\amp -1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

Next, we will consider the reflection about the <m>y</m>-axis.

<me>
    \mathbf{i}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}\quad\text{maps to}\quad\begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\end{bmatrix},
</me>

  
  
<me>
    \mathbf{j}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}\quad\text{maps to}\quad\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

  
  Thus, the matrix that induces the reflection about the <m>y</m>-axis is
  
<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}-1\amp 0\\0\amp 1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
    </p>
</exploration>
  
<p> 
  Now we will turn our attention to transformations that reflect the plane about the line <m>y=mx</m>.  We will assume that <m>m\neq 0</m>.
  
  Consider the vector <m>\mathbf{i}</m> and its reflection. 
</p> 


<image width="55%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]

  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-2,0)--(2,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-2)--(0,2);

  \draw[line width=1pt](-1,2)node[below, left]{\(y=mx\)}--(1,-2);
  \draw[thin, dashed](-2,-1.5)node[below]{\(y=-\frac{1}{m}x+\frac{1}{m}\)}--(2,0.5);
  \node[red] at (0.5, 0.2)   (a) {\(\mathbf{i}\)};
  \node[] at (-0.5, -0.2)   (b) {\(T(\mathbf{i})\)};
  \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt, -stealth, red](0,0)--(1,0);
  \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt, -stealth](0,0)--(-0.6,-0.8);
  \draw[dashed] (0,0) circle (1);
 
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>


   
<p> 
   Observe that the head of the image vector, <m>T(\mathbf{i})</m>, will lie on the line that passes through <m>(1,0)</m> and is perpendicular to the line <m>y=mx</m>.  The equation of this line is given by
   
   <men xml:id="eq-reflectionline"> 
   y=-\frac{1}{m}x+\frac{1}{m}.
   </men>
   
 The head of <m>T(\mathbf{i})</m> will also lie on the circle with equation
   
<me>
    x^2+y^2=1.
</me>

   
   
   To find the image of <m>\mathbf{i}</m> we need to determine where the line  <m>y=-\frac{1}{m}x+\frac{1}{m}</m> intersects the circle.  Substitution gives us
   
   
<me>
    x^2+\left(-\frac{1}{m}x+\frac{1}{m}\right)^2=1.
</me>

   After a little algebra we get
   
<me>
    \left(1+\frac{1}{m^2}\right)x^2-\left(\frac{2}{m^2}\right)x+\left(\frac{1}{m^2}-1\right)=0.
</me>

   The quadratic formula yields 
   
<me>
    x=1\quad\text{and}\quad x=\frac{1-m^2}{m^2+1}.
</me>

   
   The solution <m>x=1</m> corresponds to the head of the vector <m>\mathbf{i}</m>. 
   So, the <m>x</m>-component of <m>T(\mathbf{i})</m> is <m>x=\frac{1-m^2}{m^2+1}</m>. 
   We find the <m>y</m>-component of <m>T(\mathbf{i})</m> by substituting <m>x=\frac{1-m^2}{m^2+1}</m> into <xref ref="eq-reflectionline"/>.
   
<me>
     y=-\frac{1}{m}\left(\frac{1-m^2}{m^2+1}\right)+\frac{1}{m}=\frac{2m}{m^2+1}.
</me>

   Thus, the image of <m>\mathbf{i}</m> under this reflection is given by
   
<me>
    T(\mathbf{i})=\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1-m^2}{m^2+1}\\\frac{2m}{m^2+1}\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

   
Next we need to find the image of <m>\mathbf{j}</m>. The head of <m>T(\mathbf{j})</m> is located at one of the intersections of line <m>y=-\frac{1}{m}x+1</m> and the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>.  
</p> 


<image width="55%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]

  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-2,0)--(2,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-2)--(0,2);
 
  \draw[line width=1pt](-1,2)--(1,-2)node[above, right]{\(y=mx\)};
  \draw[thin, dashed](-2,0)--(2,2)node[below,right]{\(y=-\frac{1}{m}x+1\)};
  \node[blue] at (0.15, 0.5)   (a) {\(\mathbf{j}\)};
  \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt, -stealth, blue](0,0)--(0,1);
  \draw[-\gt ,line width=1pt, -stealth](0,0)--(-0.8,0.6)node[above, left]{\(T(\mathbf{j})\)};
  \draw[dashed] (0,0) circle (1);
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
 

<p> 
We leave it to the reader to verify that
<men>\label{eq:imageofj} T(\mathbf{j})=\begin{bmatrix}\frac{2m}{m^2+1}\\\frac{m^2-1}{m^2+1}\end{bmatrix}</men>

This reflection is induced by the matrix 

<me>
    M_{y=mx}=\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1-m^2}{m^2+1} \amp  \frac{2m}{m^2+1}\\\frac{2m}{m^2+1} \amp  \frac{m^2-1}{m^2+1}\end{bmatrix}=\frac{1}{1+m^2}\begin{bmatrix}
1-m^2 \amp  2m \\
2m \amp  m^2-1
\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
</p> 




<identity xml:id="form-reflection">
    <title>Reflection about the line <m>y=mx</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A matrix transformation induced by
<men xml:id="eq-reflectionymx">
M_{y=mx}=\frac{1}{1+m^2}\begin{bmatrix}
1-m^2 \amp  2m \\
2m \amp  m^2-1
\end{bmatrix}
</men>

reflects the plane about the line <m>y=mx</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</identity>

<p> 
Note that when <m>m=0</m>, expression <xref ref="eq-reflectionymx"/> is consistent with the reflection matrix you found in <xref ref="init-reflectionxyaxes"/>.
</p>


